MapGD) and Community Empowerment -- tInvestigating Citizen Participation in Plans for Lamu Port, Kenya -- tHydroelectricity, Water Rights, Community Mapping, and Indigenous Toponyms in the Queuco River Basin -- tSentinels of Carelmapu: Participatory Community Monitoring to Protect Indigenous Marinescapes in Southern Chile -- tInequality in Water Access for South Africa’s Small-Scale Farmers Amid a Climate Crisis: Past and Present Injustices in a Legal Context -- tActivist Citizen Science: Building Water Justice in South Africa -- tCollective Resilience for Climate Justice -- tConflicting Perspectives in the Global South Just Transition Movement: A Case Study of the Mpumalanga Coal Region in South Africa -- tSaving Our “Common Home”: A Critical Analysis of the “For Our Common Home” Campaign in Alberta -- tAction Research for Climate Justice: Challenging the Carbon Market and False Climate Solutions in Mozambique -- tYouth Climate Activism: Mobilizing for a Common Future -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aClimate catastrophe throws into stark relief the extreme, life-threatening inequalities that affect millions of lives worldwide. The poorest and most marginalized, who are least responsible for the consumption and emissions that create climate change, are the first and hardest impacted, and the least able to protect themselves. Climate justice is simultaneously a movement, an academic field, an organizing principle, and a political demand. Building climate justice is a matter of life and death. Climate Justice and Participatory Research offers ideas and inspiration for climate justice through the creation of research, knowledge, and livelihood commons and community-based climate resilience. It brings together articulations of the what, why, and how of climate justice through the voices of energetic and motivated scholar-activists who are building alliances across Latin America, Africa, and Canada. Exemplifying socio-ecological transformation through equitable public engagement, these scholars, climate activists, community educators, and teachers come together to share their stories of participatory research and collective action. Grounded in experience and processes that are currently underway, Climate Justice and Participatory Research explores the value of common assets, collective action, environmental protection, and equitable partnerships between local community experts and academic allies. It demonstrates the negative effects of climate-related actions that run roughshod over local communities’ interests and wellbeing, and acknowledges the myriad challenges of participatory research. This is a work committed to the practical work of transforming socio-economies from situations of vulnerability to collective wellbeing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aClimate justicexInternational cooperation. 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspects. 0aResilience (Ecology). 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh  aafrican studies.  acitizen science.  aclimate activism.  aclimate justice.  aclimate research.  acommons.  aecological economics.  afisheries.  afood and agriculture.  aindigenous studies.  aknowledge commons.  alatin american studies.  aparticipatory research.  aredd.  awater.  ayouth climate activism.1 aAbassombe, Guy Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdam, Ferrial, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlbagli, Sarita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlmonacid, Joaquin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAraos, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul